{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17659198","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17659198"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T23:03:32+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T23:03:32+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20849"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"20849","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/20849"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13724"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96438"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"13724","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/13724"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20849"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79087"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"11597"},{"type":"tags","id":"12333"},{"type":"tags","id":"12674"},{"type":"tags","id":"12795"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"33040"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33041"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96438","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/96438"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes indirect-acting carcinogens?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Require metabolic conversion to become ultimate carcinogens","Directly damage DNA without requiring metabolic activation","Induce cancer only after prolonged exposure of several decades","Act exclusively through receptor-mediated mechanisms","Primarily cause cancer through epigenetic modifications"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERequire metabolic conversion to become ultimate carcinogens\u003C/strong\u003E correctly describes indirect-acting carcinogens. These compounds are not carcinogenic in their original form but must undergo metabolic activation, primarily by cytochrome P-450-dependent monooxygenases, to be converted into ultimate carcinogens that can damage DNA and initiate carcinogenesis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDirectly damage DNA without requiring metabolic activation\u003C/strong\u003E - This describes direct-acting carcinogens, not indirect-acting carcinogens, which require metabolic processing.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPrimarily cause cancer through epigenetic modifications\u003C/strong\u003E - While some carcinogens may affect epigenetic mechanisms, indirect-acting carcinogens are defined by their need for metabolic activation, not by their mechanism of action after activation.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAct exclusively through receptor-mediated mechanisms\u003C/strong\u003E - Indirect-acting carcinogens are defined by their requirement for metabolic activation, not by receptor-mediated effects.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInduce cancer only after prolonged exposure of several decades\u003C/strong\u003E - This describes a temporal characteristic of some carcinogens but does not define indirect-acting carcinogens, which are classified based on their need for metabolic activation.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EExamples of indirect-acting carcinogens include polycyclic aromatic hydrocarbons like benzo[a]pyrene found in cigarette smoke and grilled meats, and aromatic amines used in dye and rubber industries. Individual susceptibility to these carcinogens varies based on genetic polymorphisms in the enzymes responsible for their activation or detoxification.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Indirect-acting carcinogens require metabolic conversion by enzymes to become active carcinogens.","Cytochrome P-450-dependent monooxygenases are the primary enzymes responsible for metabolic activation of indirect carcinogens.","Genetic polymorphisms in metabolic enzymes affect individual susceptibility to chemical carcinogenesis."],"references":["Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2020. Chapter 7; page 322."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79087"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20849"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79087","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/79087"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-01T14:09:36+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-01T14:10:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13724"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96438"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"11597","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11597"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Neoplasia","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":6,"createdAt":"2025-02-26T20:57:41+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-02-26T20:57:41+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"18"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"12333","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/12333"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Carcinogenic agents and their cellular interactions","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2025-03-14T22:46